    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! That's a classic scaling issue, and while it might seem like a minor annoyance, it's actually a very important thing to fix before you start training your model.\n\nThink of it this way: if you have a model that needs to learn from both a tiny, fast-moving goblin and a massive, slow-moving dragon, the dragon's movements will completely drown out the goblin's signals. The model will just focus on the big numbers (the dragon) and ignore the small ones (the goblin), because in the world of gradients, big numbers are always louder than small ones.\n\nNormalization is like putting both the goblin and the dragon on the same scale so they can actually communicate. Without it, your model is essentially shouting at the dragon while whispering to the goblin, and the whisper gets lost in the noise.\n\nHere is why it really matters:\n\n1.  **Gradient Stability**: When your features have wildly different scales (like 0-1 vs 1000-5000), the gradients during backpropagation will be huge for the big features and tiny for the small ones. This causes the optimization process to bounce around wildly, like a goblin trying to climb a",
